Request.name: Update the specified time entry.
Request.description:
See [Display the specified time entry.](#display-the-specified-time-entry) for the returned attributes.
Omitted fields will not be updated, even when using the `PUT` method.
A time entry's title and project fields can not both be empty.

body.text:
{
    "start_date": "2019-01-01T00:00:00+00:00",
    "end_date": "2019-01-01T01:00:00+00:00",
    "project": "Unproductive child project",
    "title": "Client Meeting",
    "notes": "Some more detailed notes"
}

Request.name: Display the specified time entry.
Request.description: The following attributes will be returned: - `self`: A link to the entity itself, relative to the API root. - `start_date`: The time entry's start date and time. - `end_date`: The time entry's end date and time. - `duration`: The time entry's total duration, in seconds. - `project`: The project this time entry is associated with. - `title`: The time entry's title. - `notes`: The time entry's notes. - `is_running`: Whether the time entry is currently running. Only one time entry can be running at any given time.

Request.name: Create a new time entry.
Request.description:
See [Display the specified time entry.](#display-the-specified-time-entry) for the returned attributes.
The title and project fields can not both be empty.

body.text:
{
    "start_date": "2019-01-01T00:00:00+00:00",

Request.name: Return a list of time entries.
Request.description:
See [Display the specified time entry.](#display-the-specified-time-entry) for the returned attributes. Items are ordered descending by their `start_date` field.
If no date range filter is provided via `start_date_min` and `start_date_max`, this query returns all time entries between midnight (UTC) 30 days ago and end of day (UTC) today.

parameters.name: start_date_min
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to time entries whose start date is equal to or later than this parameter.

parameters.name: start_date_max
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to time entries whose start date is equal to or earlier than this parameter.

parameters.name: projects[]
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to time entries associated with the given project. Can be repeated to include time entries from several projects.

parameters.name: search_query
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to time entries whose title and/or notes contain all words in this parameter. The search is case-insensitive but diacritic-sensitive.

parameters.name: is_running
parameters.comment: If provided, returns only time entries that are either running or not running.

parameters.name: include_project_data
parameters.comment: If true, the properties of the time entry's project will be included in the response.

parameters.name: include_child_projects
parameters.comment: If true, the response will also contain time entries that belong to any child projects of the ones provided in `projects[]`.

parameters.name: include_team_members
parameters.comment: If true, the response will also contain time entries that belong to other team members, provided the current user has permission to view them.

Request.name: Stop the currently running timer.
Request.description: Returns the stopped timer's attributes as listed under [Display the specified time entry.](#display-the-specified-time-entry).

Request.name: Start a new timer.
Request.description:
This also stops the currently running timer if there is one. See [Display the specified time entry.](#display-the-specified-time-entry) for the returned attributes.
The title and project fields can not both be empty.

Request.name: Return a list containing all the teams you are a member of.
Generate a report that can contain both time entries and app usage.
Request.description:
Returns a JSON array with several rows; each row includes the total duration (in seconds) belonging to the corresponding other (configurable) columns. The `include_app_usage` and `include_team_members` parameters govern whether to include app usage (otherwise, only time entries are returned) as well as data for other team members.
The `start_date_min`, `start_date_max`, `projects`(also see `include_child_projects`) and `search_query` parameters allow filtering the returned data.
The `columns`, `project_grouping_level`, `include_project_data`, and `sort` parameters govern the presentation of the returned data.
Fetching large amounts of app usage can put a substantial amount of load on our servers, so please be mindful before frequently requesting large amounts of data using this API.

parameters.name: include_app_usage
parameters.comment: Whether to include app usage in the report. If false, only time entries are returned. Default: `false`

parameters.name: include_team_members
parameters.comment: If true, the response will also contain time entries that belong to other team members, provided the current user has permission to view them. Default: `false`

parameters.name: start_date_min
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to data whose start date is equal to or later than this parameter.

parameters.name: start_date_max
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to data whose start date is equal to or earlier than this parameter.

parameters.name: projects[]
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to data associated with the given project. Can be repeated to include time entries from several projects. If you would like to include time entries that are not assigned to any project, you can provide an empty string, i.e. `projects[]=`

parameters.name: include_child_projects
parameters.comment: If true, the response will also contain time entries that belong to any child projects of the ones provided in `projects[]`. Default: `false`

parameters.name: search_query
parameters.comment: Restricts the query to time entries whose title and/or notes contain all words in this parameter. The search is case-insensitive but diacritic-sensitive. Note: this parameter can not be used when app usage is included.

parameters.name: columns[]
parameters.comment: Which columns to show. The `user` column is ignored if `include_team_members` is false. Possible values: `project`, `title`, `notes`, `timespan`, `user`. Default: `user`, `project`, `title`. `start_date` and `end_date` is shown when `timespan` column is sent.

parameters.name: project_grouping_level
parameters.comment: When this argument is provided, report lines for projects below the given level will be aggregated by their parent project on the given level. For example, when `project_grouping_level` is 0, all times in sub-projects will be counted towards the corresponding project on the "root" (i.e. highest) level in the project tree. Can be a non-negative integer or -1. The default is -1, which indicates no grouping (i.e. all projects will be returned, regardless of how deep they are in the hierarchy). Requires `columns[]` to contain `project`.

parameters.name: include_project_data
parameters.comment: If true, the properties of each line's project will be included in the response. Requires `columns[]` to contain `project`.

parameters.name: sort[]
parameters.comment: Sort the results by the given column. Prepend column name with a dash (`-`) to sort descending. Default: `-duration`. Examples: `sort[]=-duration` -> Sort descending by duration. `sort[]=user&sort[]=-duration` -> Sort ascending by user, then descending by duration.

Request.name: Delete the specified project and all of its children.
Update the specified project.
Request.description:
See [Display the specified project.](#display-the-specified-project) for the returned attributes.
Omitted fields will not be updated, even when using the `PUT` method.
Changing a project's parent or children is currently not possible.

Request.name: Display the specified project.
Request.description:
The following attributes will be returned: - `self`: A reference to the entity itself, relative to the API root. - `title`: The project's title. - `title_chain`: An array containing the title of the project and all its ancestors. Example: `["Parent", "Child"]` - `color`: The project's color, in hexadecimal format (`#RRGGBB`). Example: `#FF0000` - `productivity_score`: The project's productivity rating, between -1 (very unproductive) and 1 (very productive). Example: `1` - `is_archived`: Whether the project has been archived. Defaults to false. Example: `false` - `parent`: A reference to the enclosing project. - `children`: The project's children.
Child projects are provided as references; i.e. they only contain the self attribute.
